column168: Driver stopped in Vinton,La to eat breakfast. Checked trailer found no leaks. Driver drove down I-10 east to Hwy 27 turning right, then to Hwy 108 Turning right, and then turned left on to John Brannon Rd. Stopped at Waste Management to check in.  Driver noticed dripping from barrel of trailerat 0800. Waste Management personel coming to work notice spillage on the roadway to the plant. Driver climbed on top of trailer and notice the gasket on the dome lid had been over tightened and had leaked.  Driver opened dome lid, repostioned gasket and secured dome lid. Pressure up trailer and no leaks detected. Driver call Safety Department at 0805. Safety called LASP hot line at 0820. Called out ES&H clean up company to handle spill. ES&H arrived at 1000 ES&H, DEQ and the local FD are onsite.  There are 5 spill areas with 2 being pretty heavy.  They plan to apply bi-carb to the spill and then have the FD wash the material off the roadway.  DEQ is okay with this approach.  They are also going to hire an off-duty police officer to provide traffic control.  They advise it may take a while to get this done, that being 8 to 10 hours. After this is complete they will wipe down the trailer and the driver will enter plant and unload product.
column169: retrain driver on proper way to secure dome lid.

column168: On July 1, 2011, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container SMLU541313-3 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (POLYESTER RESIN KITS). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

column168: Tank car TILX 110376 was reported venting during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and no additional venting was observed when the now cordoned-off TILX 110376 remained motionless. BNSF mechanical and hazardous material responders inspected TILX 110376 finding the Salco Quick Inspect safety vent's rupture disc holder or the 'Quick Inspection Body' (QIB) with its top cap (plug) and the frangible disc missing. The aforementioned missing appurtenances were found on the ground approximately 150 yards away where TILX 110376 was currently located. This QIB had the top cap (plug) still securely attached. The bottom threads of the QIB appeared damaged with approximately 75% of the bottom thread missing. The 165 psig frangible disc was found intact (not burst). A new QIB with top cap (plug) was installed along with a new 165 psig frangible disc. Seal BNSF HAZMAT 001822 was applied. Repairs were completed by 0740 hrs. CDT, 7/01/2011.

column168: A boxed outboard motor was shipped as freight with a hidden undeclared wet battery in side (battery loaded in the box on its side).  During off loading at the destination, the crew discovered the box to be wet.  The crew inspected further and found that a wet battery had leaked inside the box.   The wet box was removed from the aircraft and the wet/damp spot in the aircraft was imediatly wiped up.   Freight was left out at destination.   The previously wiped up residue was than re-cleaned by maintenance when the aircraft returned to Anchorage from Nome.  No damage was noted.  The spilled residue from the wet box did not flow free in the a/c, only the wet box came in contact with the aircraft.
column169: The shipper was contacted and notified.   This was a hidden non-declared shipment.

column168: Driver was enroute to deliver the four drums of phosphoric acid solution when he was notified to make a pick up of metal grating.  The metal grating was loaded up against the poly drums with no dunnage placed between the metal grating and drums.  The driver proceeded down the road to deliver the drums when a vehicle pulled out in front of him.  He hit the brakes and the metal grating slid forward into the poly drums resulting in a small puncture.  Leak was contained to the trailer itself until the contract team arrived to perform the clean up.
column169: Driver failed to follow established procedures due to being in a hurry and not placing dunnage to protect the freight.  Expect the unexpected to happen...block, brace, and use dunnage to protect the freight no matter how short a distance the travel is.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for reloading into other trailers destined for various intended waste disposal facilities.  An overpack drum was being lifted by the forklift along the large groove below the lid.  Enough force was applied that the lid popped off allowing vapors from the fuming material to escape into the air in the trailer.  The forklift operator continued backing the drum out of the trailer for approximately 15 seconds, while another employee was steadying the drum.  A response crew was notified who donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and secured the lid back on the drum.  One of the exposed employees began to have shortness of breath and racing heartbeat.  He went to the emergency room of the local hospital and after 3 hours of obervation was released after they symptoms eased.  The drum was loaded onto the trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility after being properly closed.
column169: The forklift operator should not have attempted to lift the drum with all of the weight of the load against the lid, causing the lid to come off.  The operator was retrained in proper forklift operation.

column168: A sea container was brought to the dock at the intended waste disposal facility for unloading.  It was noticed that there was some black, viscous liquid pooled on top of one the the drums and evidence that it had leaked down the side, onto the pallet and trailer floor.  No material escaped the inside of the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The leaking drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container and the spilled material was cleaned up with an absorbent material which was also placed into the salvage container.  The trailer was then unloaded and placed back into service.
column169: When inspecting the drum, it appeared that a weld along the bung had broken, allowing the material to escape.  The origin location was notified and advised the generator to use care when using old used drums for transport.

column168: A van trailer had been loaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility and was awaiting dispatch to the intended waste disposal facility.  During a routine yard check, a slight drip was noticed coming from the trailer onto the pavement.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A super sack was found leaking, split along a seam.  It was overpacked into suitable salvage drums and the trailer and pavement was cleaned with a suitable absorbant material.  The cleanup material was also placed into the salvage drums.  The Ohio EPA was notified and assigned case number 1107-18-2291 to the incident.  The truck was then dispatched to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The origin was notified to use better care in loading super sacks.  All of the material was loaded on one side, causing the weight distribution to all be against one seam.

On Thursday, July 9, 2011 at approximately 2255 hours PTRA switch crews working at American Yard noticed product leakin from the manway area on tank car GATX 17716. They immediately reported the incident to the Yardmaster on duty. M&M Protection was notified to respond to the incident. Upon arrival they found that the tank car did not have a gasket applied when loaded, or it fell into the tank when the shipper closed the lid. M&M installed a new gasket and sealed the tank car. They pressure washed the tank and ground with a water based solution to break down the oil. The scene was cleared at approximately 0230 hours and the car was released for movement to Houston Fuel Oil Terminal.
column169: The shipper on the waybill, JW Stone Oil Distributors was notified of the incident and is investigating the failure. They indicated that the tank car was shipped from Murphy Oil in Superior Wisconsin.

column168: A dump body trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended Clean Harbors waste management facility. Upon stopping at the Clean Harbors Braintree MA facility to obtain pre-note paperwork for cross boarder crossing into Ontarion CN, the drive conducted a routine load check and discovered a small amount of material coming from the rear door of the dump body trailer. The driver immediately placed a containment pail under the rear door and contacted his home dispatcher to request a response crew. Upon notification, a Clean Harbors response crew was dispatched to the scene where the response crew tighted the rear door which stopped the leak and added the spill material back into the dump trailer. The Mass DEP was notified (report RTN-233) along with the Braintree Fire Dept. The load was rejected back to the customers site for reloading to insure proper load closure for contuinued transportation to intended disposal facility. The load was secured and reloaded for shipment the following day.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been re instructed to insure that a comprehensive inspection of a container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation. In addition, the shipper was notified and instructed to insure that loads are secure upon shipment.

THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF OBVIOUS DAMAGE TO THE EXTERANL CARTON DUE TO ANY KIND OF MISTREATMENT.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND CONTAINED BY A DESIGNATED RESPONDER AND ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. THERE WAS NO INNER PACKING MATERIAL TO KEEP THE CANS FROM CONTACTING THE EXTERNAL CARTON.  THIS RESULTED IN THE SPILLAGE OF 0.33 GALLONS OF PAINT.  THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL HAS BEEN PLACED IN THE FACILITY WASTE DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL THROUGH THE UPS DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.

column168: On 07/02/2011 at 1306 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Stanley yard in Walbridge, OH, discovered PROX 43107, a loaded tank car of ETHANOL ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS, leaking from the top of the tank car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, MC Services, was notified via CHEMTREC report 2011-07-02-00094; local, state and/or federal agencies were notified as applicable. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found ten (10) of the eleven (11) securement nuts missing on the mounting flange for the service equipment inside of the "bread box".  SWS made a temporary repair and the tank car was held awaiting appropriate repairs arranged by the shipper through a mobile tank car repair facility.     Cause Code:  300  NARRI:  5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80    This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On July 4,2011 at 1750 hours,. personnel in the CSXT Barr Yard discovered GATX 200586, a loaded tank car of Alcohol NOS, leaking from the manway area during switching operations. The car was isolated; A-C Big River Resources was notified via CHEMTREC #20110704-00086.  SWS Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 3 of 6 manway securement bolts less than tool tight and the manway gasket misaligned. The issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Jim Mock at 309-932-9977.  SWS personnel realigned the gasket and secured the manway bolts.  The car was secured and released for transportation.     This incident did require a special switching move.    A QA 7.1 Non-Conformance Report - will be submitted    NARRI Cause Code:  208    NARRI Severity Index Values:   5(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 80

column168: A BNSF switch crew in the railyard reported tank car TILX 200163 leaking product from the manway closure during normal switching operations. Spillage was evaporating after ground contact and on the side shell of TILX 200163. Movement of TILX 200163 was stopped and it was determined that it could be carefully positioned at an isolation track within the railyard to await further inspection and necessary corrective action to eliminate the leak source. The shipper was notified and immediately dispatched a nearby responder to inspect TILX 200163. The shipper responder reported that inspection of TILX 200163 revealed 2 of 8 manway securement bolts were not tool tight but only hand tight. The responder preceded to tool tightened all manway securement bolts in the appropriate sequence to secure the manway closure. All other valves and fittings were found secure. No further product release was reported from TILX 200163 during subsequent movements in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Loading or Unloading Lines; Valve Stem
column168: Upon arriving to deliver product, driver noticed product leaking from discharge piping.  Product was dripping from a pinhole at a very slow rate into containment at delivery location.  Emergency Response contractor was called in to assist in unloading product with a double-diaphragm pump to minimize leakage and process was completed without further incident.  The seat on the valve was damaged by 50% sulfuric acid.  The damage to the valve seat caused internal valve to leak into the piping going to the external valve.  The elbow on the piping going to the external valve was not lined and the 50% sulfuric acid caused the piping to leak.
column169: 1. Bottom outlet discharge trailers not to be used to haul 50% sulfuric acid.        2. Rubber lined trailers should be used to haul 50% sulfuric acid.                         3. If a Chemline trailer is to be used to haul 50% sulfuric acid, the trailer should be inspected after each use for potential damage.

column168: A box truck picked up various shipments of hazardous waste on Friday 7-15-11.  3 cubic yard boxes of hazardous waste solids were loaded by the generator and picked up Friday.  At the time of pickup they showed no signs of leaking, nor in the afternoon when he returned to the intermediate truck transfer facility.  On Monday, when the truck was being unloaded for transfer onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility, the bottom corner of the cubic yard box was soaked and there was liquid material on the floor.  Appropriate personal protective equipment was donned by the driver and the box was removed from the truck.  An absorbent material was placed onto the floor along with a cleaning compound.  The material in the box did not appear wet on the surface.  The material was shoveled out of the box into appropriate salvage drums.  It was found that some wet material had been placed between the inner plastic liner bag and the outer fiberboard portion of the cubic yard box--causing the leak.
column169: The shipper was notified of the incident and advised to use better care when loading material into the liner bags of cubic yard boxes.

column168: While doing a pretrip inspection, the driver noticed material had leaked from a van trailer containing hazardous waste onto the tires and dolly legs of the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A shipment of 22 bags of material was found to have 3 bags which were leaking some liquid material.  Some of the material had leaked and dried out onto the tires, ground and also the trailer floor.  The trailer was unloaded and the 3 leaking bags were repacked into 4 cubic yard boxes.  The trailer floor, dolly legs, tires and ground were cleaned up with a suitable cleaning compound.  The trailer was reloaded and dispatched to the intended waste disposal facility.  Illinois Emergency Management Authority was notified--incident number HM20110776.
column169: It was determined that the spill was the result of a combination of too much moisture content in the material along with excessive heat (temperatures were around 100F outside)  The shipper will examine their processes to insure against further incidents.

column168: The case of 4-1 gallon containers was crushed by a forklift that was turning on the warehouse floor and struck the case. The odor of the product was overbearing and the 2 employees who were working in the area immediately exacuated to warn the supervisor. Manager and supervisor also evacuated the building due to the odor until 3rd party spill mitigation arrived and contained the material in overpack. The product spill was contained to the cement floor. Affected area was deconned of any residue.
column169: Placement of small boxes on the floor was discussed with personnel. The container was to be loaded onto another trailer. Advised responsible loader to always place regulated materials in the designated area when on the warehouse floor. Documentation issues with employee as a warning.

column168: An inbound BNSF train crew yarding their train reported tank car PPGX 1903 on an adjacent track was emanating a product odor. The area was cordoned-off around PPGX 1903's location and BNSF responders were immediately notified. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders approached PPGX 1903 with a chemical air monitoring device. A faint product odor was detected by the responders at ground level but monitoring devices registered no readings. Intact seal PPG 016069 was removed from the valve housing cover for valve inspection. The B-end vapor valve was found 3/4 turn from full closure and this valve was closed. Air monitoring samplings indicated a steep decline of product vapor at the valve housing area after this valve was closed. Later, a contract responder reinspected the valve securement of PPGX 1903 and concluded all valves were secure and no product odor/vapor was evident at that time. These responders removed all valve closure plugs, cleaned and taped plug threads with Teflon tape. The plugs were then reinserted and tool tightened. The valve housing cover was closed and resealed with seal number 2877002.   The side specification stencil on PPGX 1903 displayed the tank qualification year of 2002 and the next qualify as 2012.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Train crew on 7/22/11 made on the ground inbound inspection of 47 car inbound BNSf interchange delivery from 2340 the on 7/21/11 and when pulling out the track to switch observed the 7th car from the locomotive UTLX208750 leaking from manway.  Car was isolated on repair track by train crew and General Manager called who then responded and found the number 2,3,4,5,6,7 manway bolts loose with the # 2 and 5 bolts disenganged from the manway. Manway was inspected and the bolts secured with star pattern at 175lbs of torque. Leak was stopped.  by observation leak was  1 gallon of liquid of less.  Stains on the side of the car indicated car had been leaking for some time.  Duration after leak was found was 30 minutes with no product hitting the ground due to the air temperature. reported to shipper at 1100 7-22-11
column169: Shipper should re-visit with all loading personel the proper securement requirements for the manway bolts on rail cars.  Have proper checklist when car is loaded and checked prior to shipment

column168: On July 4, 2011 at approx. 11:00, Clarence Corbin, a driver for Jones & Jones Trucking LLC. was hauling our trailer from the Bronx, NY facility to Haw River, NC plant.  As our trailer was traveling southbound on I-95 in Howard County, MD a 55 gallon plastic container containing Regulated Medical Waste expanded due to the hot temperature causing a 4 inch crack at the bottom side wall.  Therefore, the contents leaked out the rear of the trailer.  The driver pulled over at the rest stop.  Maryland State Trooper arrived and called in Maryland MDE Emergency Response Team, Howard County Hazmat Team, and Howard County Fire/EMS Team.  At 13:00, our in-house clean up team arrived to clean up the spill.  After the spill clean up, Maryland MDE Emergency Response Team released the trailer to our custody and escorted the trailer to our closest plant to the incident which is our Baltimore, MD plant.  The trailer arrived at our Baltimore, MD plant by 17:00.
column169: Generator was contacted about this spill.  Generator will add solidifier or absorbent materials.  This should prevent the material from expanding.

column168: The SHPX 221606, load, Butadienes, Stabilized, while being switched in the Jackson, MS rail yard 07-01-11 around 2:30am, was discovered leaking. No injuries or exposures were reported. Safety qualified emergency responders mobilized and found leak sourcing from the A-end liquid valve. Specifically, the valve was not completed closed, cracked open, and the secondary closure device (dry-loc fitting) was defective and leaking from its assembly connection around the dry-loc plunger portion of the fitting. The liquid valve was closed completely, approximately 3/8 turn, stopping the release. The dry-loc secondary closure fitting was replaced.     The total release is not exactly known by carrier, but is estimated at 2 gallons. Shipper notification has been made through Canutec to Dow Chemical, Fort Saskatchewan, AB.    Shipper Has been advised that as a result of this incident, KCS services were activated to provide for railroad safety qualified services to mitigate this incident and that KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 will apply.    Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by report preparer because exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: The incident was primarily due to a lack of concern when the trailer was loaded at the shipper.  The products were loaded on pallets and were not secured to the pallet.  There was space left between the pallets that allowed movement during transport.  The driver is also partly at fault as he should not have accepted the load for transport without insuring that the trailer was loaded as to prevent forward, backward, and side to side movement.  This is a distinct violation of company policy and the driver will be reprimanded.  Contact will also be made with Safety-Kleen, as has been done in the past, to inform them of loading requirements and their adherence to them in order for us to assume responsibility for transport of the products.
column169: The training that our drivers receive in order to be able to pick-up, secure, and safely deliver hazardous materials is extensive and sufficient.  We now must find a way to insure that every driver follows the procedure every time he picks up a load.  We have undertaken a penalty program that is severe - 1 verbal, 1 written with unpaid time-off, and 3rd violation is grounds to terminate.  These violations are for each aspect of hazardous material transportation, the loading/securing, logs in transit, speed in transit, and driver actions in the event of a mishap.  Our fines are up to $500.00 against the driver and we believe that shippers must also be held accountable for their negligence in not preparing loads properly; again, we require drivers to verify and secure prior to accepting responsibility.

column168: A rolloff box was parked at the 10 day storage yard of the shipper.  When the driver picked up the box to load onto the truck, a small amount of liquid spilled out beneath the rear door.  The tailgate gasket had deteriorated causing the leak of the liquid content of the solid sludgelike material.  The driver ceased the loading operation, tightened the door and sprayed a foam material along the leak to stop it.  A shovelful of affected soil and gravel was placed into the box.  It was returned to the generator where it was further solidified and the tailgate seal was repaired.  The material was then reloaded into the box and proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The generator should have further solidified the material prior to loading and also inspected the box more closely to insure the tailgate seal was in good working codition and properly in place.

column168: On July 8, 2011 at approximately 8:47 hours, personnel in the CSXT Berylwood Yard in Luke MD, discovered GATX 57066, a loaded tank car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine, with a strong odor coming from the car. The car was isolated and shipper, Newpage, was contacted by local CSX personnel and Chem-Tel Report #15502.  Newpage sent their personnel to the scene and found the manway gasket to be cut, torn and worn, and 4 of 6 manway securement bolts less than tool tight.  Newpage personnel replaced the gasket and secured the tank car.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  This report does not require a QA 7.1 Non-Conformance Report.    Cause Code 209  NARRI Index  5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: On 07/11/2001 at 13:20 hours, the Selkirk Hump Yard observed UTLX 209728, a loaded tank car of UN 1987, Alcohols, N.O.S., to have a slosh release from the top of the tank car during classification switching.  UTLX 209728 was isolated, the shipper Poet Biorefining was notified via Professional Emergency Resource Service (800-633-8253), NYS-DEC #1103983 and NRC #982333 where notified.  EP+S of Vermont a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched and found the PRD defective. The valve center shaft was able to be lifted from the car.  EP+S secured the PRD and bagged the valve housing. Poet Biorefining agent, Mr. Paul Rodriquez (cell 316-303-3843), was contacted and advised of the broken PRD and arranged with Union Tank Car to supply a replacement PRD that was installed by Rescar Industries, Springfield, Mass.      This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non-Conformance Report is required for this incident.    Cause Code: - 418 PRD-Valve Bent/Broken Stem  NARRI: 2(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 32
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A BNSF train crew inbounding their train in the railyard's receiving tracks reported an unusual odor emanating from standing railcars on the adjacent track.  BNSF mechanical/hazardous responders were immediately notified and inspected the rail cars in that track. Responders reported finding tank car GATX 65014 (that arrived the previous evening) with hardening product on its top shell around the safety vent area. GATX 65014 was cordoned-off. Responder's detailed inspection of GATX 65014's Salco Quick Inspect safety vent revealed that the 165 psig frangible disc within had ruptured. Responder's replaced the 165 psig frangible disc in kind and secured the safety vent without further incident by 0946 hrs. CDT, 7/28/2011. All other valves and fittings were found secure. Intact shipper seals were not disturbed. Spillage around the safety vent hardened and was not scraped off. No side shell spillage or ground impact spillage from the small amount of expelled product from the safety vent was evident.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tank car NATX 303916 (in the railyard) was reported with a fresh product stain emanating from its manway closure. BNSF Mechanical/Hazardous Material responders were immediately notified and inspected NATX 303916. Responder's inspection of NATX 303916 revealed 4 of 6 manway securement bolts were not tool tight. The manway gasket was partially hanging over the manway lid/nozzle interface. Detailed inspection of the manway gasket revealed the gasket was pinched and stretched out of alignment with sections of this gasket damaged. A new manway gasket was applied and all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened by 1430 hrs. PDT, 7/28/2011. Spillage on the shell of NATX 303916 evaporated and no ground impact was observed.

column168: FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector M. Bennett noted product coming from the top of tank car DBCX 200142 (FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S.- XYLENE) during a yard inspection at the CN Curtis Yard, Gary, IN. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. All covers, housing and valve seals were noted intact. Shipper's response contractor responded noting the thermometer well, at the pressure plate, was less than tool tight allowing product to escape during movement. Thermometer tightened and an epoxy was applied to the base of the thermometer well at the pressure plate. Tank car was pressure tested for leaks and released for movement to destination for off-loading. Shipper to home shop car for further repair.

column168: While servicing our Bobtail at a local garage following a roadside breakdown, a mechanic applied grease to a fitting on the front shaft connection of the PTO driven Liquid Propane Pump. column168: Employee was unloading trailer. He opened the trailer door, he smelled something that could be a chemical spill.  When he came across PRO 235612440, he inspected each skid to see if he could identify the spill.  He found 1 pail that had what looked like a forklift blade hole. While in transit, the flammable liquid spilled out.  Approximatley 2 gallons of the liquid leaked out onto the other pails.  The pail that was leaking was put in a salvage drum and placed in OS&D.  The other pails were cleaned thouroughly and restacked on 2 separate skids.

Packaging failed.  There was a small hole in a seam on the jug, no sign of damage to the container. Hole is on the side of the container about 1 inch from the bottom of the container, on a seam, that is part of the manufacturing. A few ounces were released, but contained by the carboard outer packaging. Container placed in an over sized container to keep hole from releasing more product.

DRIVER WAS TO UNLOAD INTO AN U.S.T. AT CUSTOMER LOCATION. DRIVER CONNECTED HIS CO-AXLE DROP FITTING TO THE U.S.T. FILL LINE. DRIVER THEN CONNECTED HIS UNLOADING HOSE TO THE FITTING AND TO THE TRANSPORT TRAILER.   NOTE HERE- THE CO-AXLE DROP FITTING HAS TWO CAM-LOCK FITTINGS ON IT- ONE IS FOR PRODUCT UNLOADING AND THE OTHER IS FOR GASOLINE VAPOR RECOVERY (WHICH IS NOT USED FOR DIESEL FUEL). THE VAPOR OUTLET IS TO BE CAPPED WHEN IT IS NOT BEING USED.   THE DRIVER FAILED TO PLACE THE CAP ON THE VAPOR OUTLET ON THE CO - AXLE FITTING AND HE OPENED THE UNLOADING VALVES TO BEGIN UNLOADING PRODUCT-AS SOON AS PRODUCT STARTED TO FLOW INTO TANK, SOME PRODUCT BACKED UP INTO THE VAPOR RETURN AND LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND THROUGH THE UNCAPPED OPENING. DRIVER SHUT DOWN VALVES AND CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP PRODUCT THAT SPILLED. THIS WAS TOTAL DRIVER ERROR - NO EQUIPMENT FAILURE.  .
column169: DRIVER IN THIS CASE WAS AN EXPERIENCED PETROLEUM TRANSPORT DRIVER. DRIVER KNOW NOT TO UNLOAD PRODUCT AND THE PROCEDURES TO FOLLOW. HE ALSO WAS AWARE THAT IT IS PROCDURE TO DOUBLE CHECK EVERYTHING BEFORE OPENING ANY VALVES. DRIVER IN THIS CASE "THOUGHT" THE CAP WAS ON THE FITTING BUT DUE TO LACK OF ATTENTION TO DETAIL, FAILED TO NOTE THAT CAP WAS NOT IN PALCE AND ALSO APPARENTLY FAILED TO DOULB ECHECK ALL CONNECTIONS BEFORE STARTING TO UNLOAD PRODUCT. DRIVER ERROR-FAILED TO FOLLOW PROCEDURE. ACTION TAKEN AGAINST THE DRIVER FOR THIS ERROR IN FAILUIRE TO FOLLOW PROCEDURES.   NOTE: ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THIS CONCRETE PAD AND WAS CLEANED UP AND REMOVED FROM SITE AND WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. USED CATOR ABSORBENT FOR CLEAN UP.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: During the preload operation at the Norfolk, VA Package Center, a smaller UPS operation, employees observed a cloud thought to be smoke rising from a package as it moved on a conveyor belt. The cloud obscured the source package. The facility was evacuated as a precaution and 911 was called. After arriving on scene, the fire department determined to follow a protocol for a bomb threat because the nature of the source package was unknown. Also present were VA State Police and FBI. After considerable time and use of a robot to try to retrieve the source package, no evidence of a bomb was found. Eventually the package involved was determined to hold a fire extinguisher (dry powder), which had activated while moving on the belt. The package had been shipped in accordance with new LTD QTY provisions, displaying the LTD QTY marking. The safety pin for the fire extinguisher had been allowed to come loose because the plastic security tie had broken and the fire extinguisher shifted within the package, activating the discharge lever.

column168: TILX 303191, load, Ammonia, Anhydrous, was discovered leaking in the Kansas City yard. The tank car emitted an odor and an audible hiss sound from the pressure plate connection at four bolts toward the A-end. No exposure or injury is reported. Tightening the pressure plate did stop the release . This car built up 205 psi in the afternoon heat which help to find this leak. There was one pressure plate nut, at the leak, which was two turns loose. The other three bolts, at the leak area, were one turn loose. Once tightened the leak stopped.  It was recommended to the shipper to review shop records to communicate this issue with last home-shop that had pressure plate off for root cause determination.    The shipper offered this tank car into transportation with the tank closures not completely tight. KCS emergency services were activated to provide for railroad safety qualified services to mitigate this emergency (e.g., special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, management oversight, train/yard crew delay).  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 will apply for these services..    Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by report preparer because exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: On July 15th Roeder Cartage traveled to Procter & Gamble in Cincinnati, Ohio to  load Spent Sulfuric Acid ( ESP Drippings per Procter & Gamble ). This process has  been done and transported for the past 12 months with no incident. P & G  employees load the product accordingly to legal transport weight. The trailer is  sealed and verified secure by the driver, placard 1832.  In transit the driver routinely stops to check the trailer as verified by GPS tracking.  The last verified stop was approximately one hour and forty five minutes in  Okawville, Illinois prior to the release.  The shipment was traveling West on I-44 in Missouri approximately 60 miles west  of St. Louis on I-44 West bound en route San Diego, Ca. We presume that a  chemical reaction had started time and the trailer started to release built up  pressure in barreL This was from a reaction of the spent drippings. The trailer  pressure reliefvalve is set to relieve pressure at between 32 to 35 pounds. The air  gauge on the trailer was recording 38 pounds at the times of venting, or releases.  This difference in registered pressures is in the gauges as they are not precisely  exact. The pressure relief functioned exactly how it is designed operate. If it did not there was a good possibility that the trailer could have blown up causing massive  damages.  The truck was stopped by Sullivan, Missouri police after getting a report that a  tanker was releasing vapors and liquid. After stopping the truck/trailer the officer  approached in a wide path on the right side of the unit. At this time the pressure  was released and the officer was consumed in vapors. The Roeder Cartage driver  put on his respirator and pulled the officer from the vapors preventing more serious  injuries. He was transported to the local hospital where he was treated and released. Emergency responders were called and I-44 was closed in both the East and West lanes.  On Saturday July 16th the road was reopened at approximately 4:00 A.M. Central  time. The unit was first moved to a local access road with a parking area. This is  where the evacuation took place with a local motel nearby and additional  businesses. Later that morning the unit was moved to field in the town of Bourbon,  Missouri approximately six miles away. This is owned by the town and the fire  department. At this site the trailer was then connected to a series of scrubber  systems with totes of water. This was to relieve the pressure in the trailer and to cool the product. At this time the trailer was warm and the spent acid was guessed to be hot. There was still an ongoing chemical reaction going on inside the trailer as the pressure was not reducing. By Tuesday July 19th the pressure was subsiding and on Thursday July 21st the reaction and pressure was zero.  On Thursday Clean Harbors Response team along with Procter & Gamble response  employees initiated trying to pump off the spent into totes. That day two totes ere  filled before burning the pump
column169: Procter & Gamble is doing an internal evaluation and investigation. They are doing  sampling and testing of the spent product. I am sure we or our insurance carrier,  Great West Casualty will be informed.  This particular barrel was a new stainless tank. This was the second spent load to be transported. The first also was P & G spent acid. There was no recordable residue  remaining in the barrel. The trailer was transported to Clean Harbors site in  Cincinnati, Ohio on their drop-deck trailer. The trailer was wrapped and secured  and inspected by the Missouri Department of Transportation before being moved.  Roeder Cartage does not plan on using this trailer again. We are not in confidence  of the integrity of the barrel. We consider this a Procter & Gamble issue and are  willing to scrap the trailer.  I am sure that Procter & Gamble will do everything in its ability to find a cause for this problem. I am sure that safeguards will be put in place before we transport  another load of spent acid for them.

column168: Was reported that tank car GATX 80226, a load of PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S., was discovered leaking while being switched at the KCS Shreveport yard. The KCS responded to the release, along with Jay Hardy (Louisiana State Police, LSPD) and Demessia Hicks (Calumet). The cause of the release was found to be oringinating from a loose liquid line valve connection, where the Liquid valve bolts to the tank car four bolt flange.     Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by report preparer because exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.     KCS emergency services were activated to provide for railroad safety qualified services to mitigate this emergency (e.g., special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory notification reports).  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  During handling at the Lynden Transport, Inc. facility, one (1) 330-gallon tote was punctured by a forklift.  Approximately 55 gallons of free product were released to the warehouse floor.  Lynden Transport, Inc. personnel applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid.  TAS Environmental Services of Fort Worth, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival, TAS Environmental Services applied additional absorbent material to the free liquid, and pumped off the remaining free product from the damaged tote, into 55-gallon drums.  The spent absorbents were recovered, and containerized along with virgin product, into five (5) 55-gallon drums.   All product was contained inside warehouse and did migrate off site or threaten to impact the environment.  Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Lynden Transport, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: UPRR Yard Master reported tank car NATX 300051 was releasing an unknown amount of product from the bottom of the tank car in the Pocatello rail yard.  Jeffrey Dukes, UPRR Hazardous Materials Manager was notified. Mr. Dukes notified UPRR Special Agent Hazardous Materials to respond.   Inspection revealed the tank car had released approximately 10 gallons of product from the bottom outlet cap.   After further inspection it was determined the bottom outlet valve was not completely shut.  The valve was shut stopping the release.  The bottom outlet cap was inspected and revealed the gasket was misaligned the gasket was aligned and the cap tigtened.   The tank car was then inspected and released to transportation.

UTLX 68983 was noted by carrier personnel with product dripping from the outside of the steam coil inlet pipe.  Car isolated and shipper notified.     Shipper representatives, Moran Environmental, responded and determined the release was originating from a location hidden by the tank car jacket.  Material was running down the outside surface of the heater coil inlet pipe indicating the release was from the tank shell due to an unknown defect, possibly as crack or corrosion.      The tank car contents was transferred to four truck tanks for delivery to the consignee.  The car was cleaned and purged and will be sent to a tank car shop for further inspection and repairs.

column168: During a truck loading operation, product began to spill from the truck dome lid. Approximately 1 gallons of product sprayed from the dome lid and contacted the ground in the loading area. The pump was stopped and the leak was controlled.
column169: Site specific procedures (SSP) were reviewed with all employees as well as best management practices (BMP) for offloading railcars. Employees were retrained and the practice of double checking the preset amounts on the pump prior to loading the truck has been implemented. Also all keys to the Scully system by pass have been removed from line employees to ensure the equipment and all its safety components are in proper working order.

column168: July 25, 2011: At approximately 650pm, NS train 14G was pulling east through CR Morrisville, PA yard on track E-2 when an NS Mechanical Department Car Inspector, performing other duties on an adjacent track, detected a strong odor, seemingly from one of the tank cars passing by.    Further inspection of valves inside protective housing by CR Risk Manager A. Richter, and Dow (shipper/consignee) Emergency Response Fire Chief C. Harvey was conducted.  Removed liquid valve quick connect cap on tank car UTLX 902476, load Butyl Acrylate (3, UN 2348, PG III).  A small amount of liquid was lying on top (exterior) of the plunger plate of the valve.  Chemical absorbant pad used to wipe off top of valve.  No further liquid release noted.  Additionally noted the quick connect closure cap with an inadequate sized gasket.  Gasket replaced the following morning by Dow representatives, and car resealed, okayed for delivery to original destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Employee was storing overpak skids of drums (4 drums per overpak) As he was putting a skid in front of another skid, his forklift blade was sticking out the back of the skid. The blade punctured (3 inch long appox by 1/16 inch tall appox) the skid behind the skid he was moving. When the empolyee noticed the puncture/leakage, he called the supervisor and they immediaelty contained the spill/leakage.
column169: We have since instructed employees while handling drums of this nature to use forklifts with blades that do not extend further than the skid. If this is not possible then they have been instructed to have a guidesman.

column168: On July 13, 2011 at approximately 12:00 FRA Hazmat Inspector Jeff Moore was inspecting in the CSX Locust Point Yard and discovered GATX 300685, a residue tank car of waste flammable liquids with a vapor leak from the top of the car. The car was isolated and consignee Clean Harbors was contacted using their emergency contact number. A CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager was dispatched to the scene and found the packing nut on the top operating/bottom outlet valve was less than tool tight. The packing nut was made tool tight and the vapor release was stopped. The car then released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.    This incident does not require a 7.1    NARRI Cause Code= 547  5(4+3+0)(2+0)= 70

column168: Tank car MWSX 29624 in the railyard was reported leaking at a top valve fitting with its valve housing cover not fully closed. MWSX 29624 was cordoned-off awaiting BNSF hazardous material responder's inspection. Responder's inspection revealed that the 3-inch liquid valve was leaking product at its threaded connection onto a threaded pipe nipple. The valve housing cover could not be secured with the current valve configuration. In order to secure the liquid valve on its threaded connection, the vacuum relief valve (VRV) was removed and a pipe plug was secured into the vacated VRV orifice. The liquid valve was tightened on its threaded connection. With the VRV removed and the liquid valve secured into its new position, the valve housing cover was able to be properly closed and sealed. Spillage on the side shell and around the valve housing area was wiped. No ground impact from spillage was reported.   The side specification stencil on MWSX 29624 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2008.  The shipper requested a FRA-OTMA to transport MWSX 29624 to the consignee for unloading.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection procerss is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: During a routine inspection at a truck stop, the driver noticed a leaking drum.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The leaking drum was found and the lid removed.  The gasket had not been properly placed in the drum when closed and was bent over, compromising the seal causing the leak.  The gasket was re-seated and the drum was torqued to the proper foot pound.  The spilled material had been cleaned up with a suitable absorbent material and placed into the leaking drum.  The trailer was then released to continue to the intended waste disposal facility.  Ohio EPA was notified and assigned case number 1107-24-2525.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: On July 25, 2011 at approximately 11:30, personnel at the CSXT Aliquippa yard in Monaca, PA, discovered tank car GATX 300856, a loaded tank car of Ammonia Solutions, leaking from the top. The car was isolated and the shipper, Terra International Canada, Inc was contacted thru CANUTEC. Federal, State, and Local authorities were notified.  Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 3 of 6 manway bolts were less than tool tight. The issue identified was corrected by SPSI personnel who tightened the bolts tool tight, decontaminated the car and cleaned up spilled material. column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Missing Component or Device
column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Railroad Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported tank car GATX 59718 leaking product from its manway closure. The FRA Inspector also found the bottom outlet cap (BOC) not tool tight (hand tight only). Fresh product was evident around GATX 59718's manway closure with product on its side shell and safety appliances. Further inspection of GATX 59718's top fittings revealed 5 of 6 manway securement bolts less than tool tight (hand tight only) and the closure plug on the vapor valve was also less than tool tight (hand tight only). A BNSF contract responder was notified and requested to secure GATX 59718, as well as, clean all spillage from GATX 59718. GATX 59718 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard in order to accomplish the aforementioned tasks.  On 8/02/2011, contract responders cleaned the spillage from the tank shell and safety appliance of GATX 59718. Also, a small amount of hardened product atop the ground ballast at the previous location of GATX 59718 was scooped up and placed inside a small waste disposal receptacle. The manway closure was inspected and the manway gasket was found missing. A new 20 inch Salco Nitrile manway nozzle gasket was installed and the manway securement bolts properly tool tightened. The intact manway seal Suncor Energy-202679 was replaced by seal TIS-5999. The vapor valve closure plug was tool tightened. The valve housing cover was sealed with seal TIS-5930. The BOC was secured. All securement was completed by 1600 hrs. MDT, 8/02/2011.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver indicated that he was traveling North on Hwy. 111, a two lane road, when he met a pickup truck pulling a pontoon boat.  The pickup truck had drifted into the path of the tanker. The tanker driver tried to stop on the shoulder of the road and allow the pickup room to pass.  The shoulder of the road did not hold and the tanker started over as it was traveling around a curve in the road.  The tanker rolled two and one half times resting on the driver side of the truck/tanker. The tanker was punctured in two places and was spilling gasoline out of the bottom puncture and no product was coming out of the puncture on the passenger side as it was lying with that side up.  Product was also leaking out of the void holes between compartments 3 and 4.  Area fire department responded and contacted local personnel to help manage scene until clean up and company personnel could arrive on scene.  Dirt was pushed up against tanker to plug hole in the tanker on the bottom side.  A guage stick was broken and put in both the top and bottom void holes where product was leaking out.  A containment ditch was also dug in the event it was needed.  Lewis Transport personnel recovered all but 1702 gallons of the product that was on the overturned tanker.  The product that was released was cleaned up by GRAKAT, an environmental company that Lewis contracted to remediate the site.  The truck/tanker was uprighted and taken to R & R Racing facility in Flemingsburg, KY. Persons on site: Kentucky State Police, Kentucky EPA, Federal EPA, GRAKAT, Local Fire Department, R & R Racing (a towing company), Homeland Security Agent, Flemingsburg County EMS, Fleming County Emergency Services and Lewis Personnel.        Agencies contacted: NRC, KY EPA.
column169: Our drivers maneuver tractor/tankers in tight situations on a daily basis.  Being on rural roadways making deliveries of petroleum products is stressful in itself. Lewis has always stressed the importance of speed and defensive driving when delivering product to rural communities.  Roadways leading to and from product delivery sites need to be maintained in a way to accommodate tractor/tanker combinations.  We like good strong shoulders in the event we need them.

column168: Late in the afternoon of Wed., 07/27/2011, a pallet of Thionex SEC was loaded onto a SEFL truck to ship to another location.  At 5:40 p.m., the SEFL driver came back to our dock complaining of a strong odor in his truck.  Upon opening the door, the smell was evident.  We unloaded all the pallets off the truck and noticed that a small puddle, about one gallon, had formed on the metal floor of the trailer.  One of our employees was instructed to don the appropriate PPE and another was asked to assemble the oildry and containers.  After outfitting in the proper PPE, the employee proceeded into the truck and absorbed the product through 2 applications of the absorbent and placed it in a 30-gallon salvage drum to be land-applied at a later date.  I walked the outside of the trailer several times and saw no evidence that the product had leaked outside of the bed of the truck.  The driver was satisfied with the clean up.  We placed the remaining product on a new pallet, reloaded the truck, and he proceeded on his route.  Best we can figure is there was a hairline crack in the jug and sometime during the loading or transport stage it was compromised.  The jug was in the bottom corner box on the pallet and cracked on the lower corner of the jug under the spout.  The pallet of material sat on our loading dock for approximately 3 hours awaiting pick up, and there was no evidence of leakage on our dock.

column168: LINE 52 ON UP TRAIN LIST (DOWX 4243) WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT 1401 BY A RESIDENT IN JEFFERSON, LA. WHO LIVES NEXT TO EAST MAIN LINE BETWEEN CAUSEWAY BLVD OVERPASS AND LABARRE RD.    JEFFERSON PARISH FIRE DEPT ARRIVED TO THE SCENE AT 1409 AND CONFIRMED THROUGH THE NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE THAT THE WINDS AT THAT TIME WERE FROM THE NORTHWEST AT 7MPH. AND THEN PROCEEDED TO INSPECT THE LEAKING TANK CAR.    AT APPROXIMATELY 1510, NOPB YARDMASTER MIKE MAJOUE' WAS NOTIFIED BY PHONE FROM 911 DISPATCHER OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE VICINITY OF CLAIBORNE CT., SCOTT ST. AND LURLINE ST. IN JEFFERSON, LA. JOHN MCCROSSEN WAS AT THE YARD OFFICE WHEN MAJOUE RECEIVED THE CALL. MAJOUE HANDED THE PHONE TO MCCROSSEN WHO TOOK THE INFORMATION FROM THE DISPATCHER. MCCROSSEN ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 1540 AFTER RETRIEVING THE UP PAPERWORK FROM THE LOCOMOTIVE ON THE TRAIN AT DECKBAR ST.     MCCROSSEN SPOKE WITH JPFD HAZ-MAT UNIT REPRESENTATIVE ROBERT DARCY WHO ADVISED THAT DOW CHEMICAL CO. HAD BEEN CONTACTED AND WERE SENDING REPRESENTATIVES FROM DOW CHEMICAL FROM PLAQUEMINE, LA. TO THE SITE. DARCY ALSO ADVISED THAT LSP HAD BEEN CONTACTED. MCCROSSEN CALLED LSP AT 1655 TO CONFIRM NOTIFICATION. SPOKE TO LSP HAZ-MAT DISPATCHER AND WAS INFORMED THAT THEY HAD BEEN NOTIFIED BY JPFD. MCCROSSEN WAS GIVEN THE FOLLOWING ITEM NUMBER  BY LSP; 11-03904.    UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (USES) WAS CONTACTED BY MCCROSSEN AT 1600 AND ARRIVED AT 1701. REPRESENTATIVES FROM USES WERE HERMAN NEWELL AND KELSEY TAMPLAIN.    THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (DEQ) REPRESENTATIVE SAVANNAH GREENBAUM ARRIVED AT 1545 TO TAKE AIR QUALITY SAMPLES APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET FROM THE LEAKING TANK CAR. SHE RECORDED NO ODORS IN THE AREA AND DEPARTED THE SCENE AT 1830 AFTER CONCLUDING HER REPORT. SHE INSTRUCTED MCCROSSEN TO CONTACT HER WHEN THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.    AT 1910, USES SUITED UP WITH THEIR HAZ-MAT GEAR AND ATTEMPED TO REPLACE THE GASKET ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET. THE WIND DIRECTION A THAT TIME WAS LIGHT AND VARIABLE. THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 1922. ACCORDING TO USES REP HERMAN NEWELL'S SUMMARY, THE TOP OPERATING/BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WOULD NOT FULLY SEAT WHICH ALLOWED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO PASS THE SEAT AND LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. HE PULLED THE CAP OFF AND CHANGED THE GASKET, RE-SECURED THE CAP AND STOPPED THE LEAK. DOW CHEMICAL REP MIKE CUTRER REQUESTED CAR BE BROUGHT BACK TO DOW FACILIYT IN PLAQUEMINE, LA.      LOCAL FRA HAZ-MAT INSPECTOR ED ERNEWEIN ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 2030 AND ADVISED MCCROSSEN WITH PROCEDURES TO OBTAIN FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL OF CAR TO UP AVONDALE FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO DOW CHEMICAL IN PLAQUEMINE, LA. MCCROSSEN ATTEMPTED TO CONTACT UP RON TINDALL AT 2052 TO OBTAIN APPROVAL TO INTERCHANGE CAR BACK TO UP BUT GOT NO ANSWER. THEN CONTACTED UP MYO JIMMY COUGET AT 2053 WHO APPROVED MOVEMENT BACK TO UP UPON RECEIPT OF FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL.    MCCROSSEN CONTACTED FRA HAZ-MAT SPECIALIST ERICH RUDOLPH IN WASHINGTON, DC AT APPROXIMATELY 2025 TO INQUIRE ABOUT THE MOVEMENT

column168: Entrained tank car UTLX 644394 in an unattended BNSF train parked in the Seligman, AZ siding track was reported leaking product from the top fitting area by passing BNSF personnel operating rail detection equipment on the main track. A BNSF Mechanical/Hazardous Material responder and a contract responder were dispatched to inspect and secure UTLX 644394. The responders reported finding the leak source at the 3 inch liquid valve's threaded connection on its threaded pipe nipple. The liquid valve was fully engaged/tool tight on its threaded connection but product was evident on the pipe nipple threads and at the pipe nipple base. Responders removed the liquid valve and observed that a section of the top 4-5 threads (portion that threads into the liquid valve) on the pipe nipple had sustained impact damage which prevented a good seal when the liquid valve was tightened onto its threads. The responder applied Teflon tape onto the liquid valves threaded connections and resecured the liquid valve onto the pipe nipple. UTLX 644394 was setout from the train and moved to another siding track.  No further product release was evident at the liquid valve connection while being monitored by the responders. Liquid spillage evaporated.   OTMA FRA-11080584 was granted to transport UTLX 644394 to its rail destination for unloading.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car GATX 205595 was reported leaking product from its manway closure during movement on the BNSF repair tracks to correct a wheel defect. No product release was observed when GATX 205595 remained motionless. Contract responders inspected GATX 205595 and reported finding the manway securement bolts tool tight, but the manway gasket was misaligned (out of its placement groove), thus negating a good seal. Also, the liquid and vapor valve closure plugs were found not in a tool tight condition (barely hand tight), but no product leakage was evident from these valve closures. The manway gasket was not damaged and it was correctly positioned. The manway securement bolts were then properly tool tightened. The valve closure plugs were tool tightened. Securement was completed by 1100 hrs. CDT, 8/01/2011. All spillage evaporated and dried residue product staining on the tank shell was wiped.  Intact manway seal numbered 0488974 was replaced with seal JJK 9589699. Intact valve housing cover seal numbered 0488975 was replaced by seal JJK 9589700.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

A FRA Hazardous Material Railroad Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported product odor emanating from tank car NATX 300995. The FRA Inspector reported the possible vapor/odor source as NATX 300995's vacuum relief valve (VRV). A BNSF contract responder was notified and inspected NATX 300995 on 8/02/2011. The responder reported finding no product vapor/odor emanating from NATX 300995's VRV. Afterwards, NATX 300995 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard in order to conduct a more thorough inspection of all valves and fittings of NATX 300995.  On 8/03/2011, a detailed inspection of NATX 300995 revealed the threaded connection at the one inch vapor valve was the vapor/odor source. The vapor leak was at the threaded connection between the vapor valve and its pipe nipple. The vapor valve and the pipe nipple were removed and the orifice plugged. Inspection of the female valve threads and the male pipe nipple threads indicated some loss of thread or thread wear on both connecting thread surfaces. A new pipe nipple and one inch vapor valve were procured and installed. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. The valve housing was sealed with seal TIS-5933. Securement was completed by 1530 hrs. MDT, 8/03/2011. No liquid product released.  Shipper requested a FRA-OTMA to allow transportation to destination for unloading NATX 300995; and then to a qualified repair facility for deemed repairs and a leakproofness test.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

TWO RESPONDERS PERFORMED PPE, CONTAINERIEZD THE SPILL AREA, THEN IMMEDIATELY BEGAN INVESTIGATING HOW THE LEAKER OCCURED AND ENSURED NO ONE WAS ILL.  AFTER THE CLEAN UP AND INVESTIGATION.  THE BOX PLUS SPILLED MATERIAL WERE BROUGHT BACK TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA FOR PROCESSING.  THE RESPONDERS NOTICED THAT THIS WAS A RE-USED BOX WITH OLD CONTINUE-FEED SHIPPING PAPERS ALONG WITH THE CURRENT LASER COMPATIBLE PAPERS.
column169: DO NOT USE RE-USED BOXES TO TRANSPORT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: A DRIVER OF A UPS TRACTOR-TRAILER NOTICED HIS TRAILER WAS ON FIRE WHEN HE STOPPED THE VEHICLE FOR A PLANNED BREAK AT APPROXIMATELY 03:48 HRS. HE SECURED THE VEHICLE AWAY FROM NEARBY BUILDINGS AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED BOTH 911 AND UPS MANAGEMENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE, REMOVING SEVERAL PACKAGES FROM THE LOAD AS THEY DID SO. DEBRIS AND REMAINING PACKAGES WERE MOVED TO THE UPS VAN NUYS HUB, FOR AN EXAMINATION OF ALL THE REMNANTS FROM THE FIRE. WHILE IT IS VERY DIFFICULT TO BE CERTAIN ABOUT THE CAUSE, SUSPICIONS FOCUS ON THE MELTED REMAINS OF A PLASTIC, BATTERY-OPERATED TOY TRICYCLE, WHICH APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN LOADED IN THE PART OF THE TRAILER FROM WHICH THE FIRE SPREAD. ACCORDING TO THE BURN PATTER. IT IS POSSIBLE THAT THE TOY HAD ACCIDENTALLY ACTIVATED AND OVERHEATED IN ITS PACKAGE, OR THAT SOME BATTERY SHORT CIRCUIT OCCURRED. POST-INCIDENT RESEARCH SHOWS THESE TOYS ARE COMMONLY POWERED BY NON-SPILLABLE LEAD-ACID BATTERIES.
column169: UPS CANNOT ESTABLISH THE EXACT REASON FOR THE FIRE SUSPECTED TO ORIGINATE FROM THE PACKAGE CONTAINING THE BATTERY-OPERATED TOY TRICYCLE, SO IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO OFFER ANY SPECIFIC RECOMMENDATIONS.

column168: Lang was unloading the tanker and filling totes. He had finished a tote and was getting ready to move the nozzle to the next tote.  The nozzle got caught on the lip of the tote. When that happened, Lang bumped the handle of the valve causing it to open. The product came out of the nozzle and sprayed product on Lang. He thinks it was diluted product from decontamination that got in his eyes.

1. 11:26 AM - DRIVER ARRIVES AT CHICAGO RECYCLING (CH) IN CHICAGO TO LOAD.  2. 11:59 AM - DRIVER SPOTS HIS TRAILER AT THE LOADING RACK AND DISCONNECTS THE POWER UNIT FROM THE TRAILER AND WAITS IN A DESIGNATED AREA.  3. 2:45 PM - DRIVER RE-CONNECTS TO THE LOADED TRAILER, COMPLETES PAPERWORK AND LEAVES CHICAGO RECYCLING (CH) EN-ROUTE TO CLEAN HARBORS CANADA IN CORUNNA ONTARIO.  4. 3:42 PM- DRIVER STOPS AT THE TA TRUCK STOP IN PORTER INDIANA TO PERFORM TIRE CHECK, NOTICES PRESSURE BUILDING ON THE TANK GAUGE INDICATING PRESSURE HAS INCREASED ON THE TANK. CLEAN HARBORS IS CONTACTED REGARDING THE DRIVERS CONCERNS.  5. 4:36 PM- THE DRIVER MOVES THE CARGO TANK TO A REMOTE PORTION OF THE TRUCK STOP AWAITING INSTRUCTIONS FROM CLEAN HARBORS.  6. 5:20 PM - CLEAN HARBORS CONFIRMED THE ANALYSIS OF THE LOAD TO BE CONSISTENT AND THE INCREASE OF PRESSURE IS PROBABLY DUE TO THE EXTREME HEAT OF THE DAY (100.4 F) AND IS INSTRUCTED TO CONTINUE ON ROUTE.  7. 6:14 PM - DRIVER STOPS AT SAWYER MICHIGAN TO INSPECT TANK AND OBSERVED INCREASING PRESSURE IN TANK. CLEAN HARBORS IS CONTACTED AGAIN NOTIFYING THEM OF THEM INCREASING PRESSURE. THE FOLLOWING IS A LIST OF EVENTS LEADING UP TO THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.     A. DRIPS ARE OBSERVED FROM ONE LOCATION ON THE BELLY OF THE TRAILER.    B. SEVERAL DRIPS ARE OBSERVED WITHIN APPROXIMATELY 20 MINS.    C. THE TRUCK STOP IS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND 911 IS CALLED.    D. THE TRAILER IS PUT ONTO VACUUM TO ASSIST IN KEEPING THE PRODUCT WITHIN THE TANK.    E. WHILE THE TANK IS ON VACUUM, THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE BEGINS TO CYCLE      INDICATING GROWING PRESSURE WITHIN THE TANK.    F. ALL TRUCKS THAT WERE PARKED IN THE VICINITY OF THE AFFECTED TRAILERS WERE NOTIFIED TO MOVE THEIR TRUCKS.    G. SEVERAL MORE AREAS OF THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER BEGIN TO LEAK WHILE VACUUM IS ON THE TANK.    H. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IS ASKED TO BRING SAND TO THE LOCATION TO DYKE THE AREA IN CONCERN OF THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER FAILING.    I. PRESSURE IS OBSERVED RELEASING THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AND THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER THROUGH THE LIQUID PRODUCT.    J. AT APPROXIMATELY 9:15 PM, THE TRAILER OVER PRESSURIZES AND RUPTURES RELEASING THE CARGO.
column169: WILL FORWARD WHEN INVESTIGATION AND SETTLEMENT IS COMPLETE

column168: CN switch crew reported product coming from the top of tank car TICX 21133 (L / Hydrochloric Acid) during normal switching operations at CN East Yard, Detroit, MI. Tank car isolated and all appropriate departments notified. CN's response team responded noting three of four nuts missing and the remaining bolt less than tool tight to the vapor line blind flange (that attaches to the tank shell), which allowed product to escape during movement. New nuts applied and flange properly secured, tank car released onto destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: WE (SOUTHERN CHEM INDUSTRIES) DID NOT GET THE OPPORTUNITY TO PARTICIPATE IN THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION. THE INVESTIGATION WAS CONDUCTED BY MOTIVA AND ABCLEAN (THE COMPANY WHO DROPPED THE TOTE). INCIDENT FACTS AS WE KNOW THEM: THE SOUTHERN CHEM DRIVER WAS PRESENT. THE ABCLEAN EMPLOYEE UNLOADED THE TOTE BY FORKLIFT. THE GROUND (SHELL/GRAVEL STAGING/PARKING AREA WAS UNLEVEL AND CONTAINED POTHOLES.  THE FORKS ON THE FORKLIFT WERE EITHER NON-LOCKING FORKS OR WERE NOT LOCKED, WE ALSO DON'T KNOW IF THE LOAD WAS PROPERLY SEATED ON THE FORKS BEFORE THE LIFT WAS MADE. WHEN THE LOAD WAS LIFTED AND THE FORKLIFT BACKED AWAY FROM THE TRUCK AND TURNED THE LOAD SHIFTED CAUSING ALL THE WEIGHT TO SHIFT TO ONE SIDE (3445 POUNDS) THAT INERTIA/SHIFT CAUSED THE TOTE TO COME OFF THE FORKS. IT WAS DISCOVERED AFTER THE 2 PIECE TOTE WAS ON THE GROUND THAT THE TOTE SEPARATED FROM ITS BASE, NO ONE KNOWS IF THE SEPARATIN OCCURRED BEFORE OR AFTER THE TOTE HIT THE GROUND. BASED ON WHAT WE CAN OBTAIN FROM WITNESSES AND THOSE WHO PARTICIPATED IN THE INVESTIGATITON WE FEEL THAT WE HAVE NO RESPONSIBLITY IN THE INCIDENT, THE CAUSES ARE MOST LIKELY FORKLIFT OPERATOR ERROR, (NOT KNOWING WHAT HE WAS LIFTING, WEIGHT ETC) AND UNLEVEL GROUND

column25: Jones-Hamilton Company by Rubicon Chemical LLC
column168: Tank car UTLX 11223, entrained on an inbound BNSF train, was reported leaking product from its side shell as this train was entering the railyard.  Train movement was stopped and the area around UTLX 11223 was cordoned-off. The local F.D. placed catch receptacles to capture the escaping product; and later installed a magnetic patch over the hole in the compromised tank shell which ended the flow of product. The hole was towards the top of the side shell between center tank and tank head. A liner failure was suspected as the cause of this corrosion breach. Responders transferred the remaining product in UTLX 11223 into another suitable tank car that was placed on an adjacent track. Afterwards, the magnetic patch was removed and the area around the 5-6 inch longitudinal hole was cleaned. Another patch was affixed over the hole and sealant applied around its perimeter. Ground spillage was treated and neutralized with applications of lime. Two spillage impacted railcars entrained behind UTLX 11223 were decontaminated.   Two BNSF track maintenance employees working on an adjacent track in the railyard of UTLX 11223's inbound location, complained of inhalation exposure from product fumes emanating from UTLX 11223. Both employees were taken to a local hospital, examined and released without any reportable injury.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was loading a load of ethanol at the loading rack when he noticed it was leaking out the back of the tank. The driver immediately stopped the flow and contacted the Terminal Manager. Approximately 200 gallons was spilled. The local terminal personnel assisted driver in putting spill pads and booms down. SWS responded to the scene and it was determined that product did reach soil and would be remediated. Arcadis was at the scene to assist in the oversight of the cleanup. No product reached any drains. It was determined that the driver had bucket drianed after his previous load but had not opened the internal belly valves prior to doing so, therefore unleaded gas had been left in the compartment that he attempted to load the ethenol on top of, causing overfill.
column169: The driver did not follow proper unloading procedure during his previous load. Should the driver had followed proper procedures the incident would not have occured. Driver will be returned to remedial training and there will be incident prevention observations conducted on him before allowed to return to duty.

column168: On July 29, 2011, during the examination of import documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container SMLU 850820-6 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (PAINT RELATED MATERIALS). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. On August 2, 2011 upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

Approximately four cups of ferric sulfate were released from a trailer. Two cups hit the ground and two cups into containment pan.  No drains impacted.  The trailer had been weighed and was 2,000# overweight.  As they were attempting to blow the product back into the RC a leak developed from a secondary valve under the trailer.    Leak was caused by a faulty valve on the trailer.
column169: The loaders will continue to perform truck arrival inspections and identify deficiencies. This trailer was returned to the carrier for repairs.

column168: Our transportation department was contacted to arrange a return shipment of US Army training devices back to our Los Angeles depot.  Type of material, quantity and weight were provided and the shipment was booked with our transportation provider.  This was an exclusive use vehicle moving directly from Fort Lewis to the depot in Los Angeles.  It was sealed (#301720) at Fort Lewis by a Javelin Joint Venture (JJV) employee after being loaded onto the trailer by a Fort Lewis forklift driver under JJV supervision.  Upon receipt at the Los Angeles depot it was discovered that an additional box (the HazMat) had been placed on a skid with other equipment.  This box contained 6 BCUs which are covered by Competent Authority CA1996080013 and was not properly documented nor were the proper notifications made to the carrier. There was no damage to the BCU's, their skid or the rest of the shipment.  There was no release of any dangerous materials.
column169: As normal practice we place the following statement on shipping correspondences that involve equipment that might contain dangerous goods:  "Please ensure you DO NOT have any Technical Manuals, BCUs or BA/BB Batteries in the CLU or transit case. Tech Manuals are an ITAR violation. BCUs and BA/BB Batteries are a HAZ MAT violation. The Javelin Joint Venture is required by law to report all violations to the Department of Transportation in accordance with 49 CFR 171.16 (Code of Federal Regulations - Title 49: Transportation). As a part of the reporting requirement, the offending shipper is reported (by name) to the Department of Transportation."  Going forward we will include this statement on ALL shipping correspondences.  All JJV personnel who are part of the Javelin Fielding team responsible for shipping equipment will be HAZMAT certified by taking HMT-150, Multi-Modal Initial Training by the Dangerous Goods Advisory Council - DGAC.  The Javelin Total Package Fielding (TPF) Guidance Manual will be updated to reflect BCU shipments.

column168: THE CLERKS WERE CALLED TO THE ORANGE BELT BECAUSE OF A BOX THAT HAD AN ODOR.  UPON OPENING THE BOX, THE CLERK FOUND A METAL CYLINDER THAT HAD A (2) FLAMMABLE LIQUID STICKER ON IT.  THE VALVE HAD COME OPEN ON THE CYLINDER, CAUSING THE CYLINDER TO VENT.  THE STICKER INDICATED THAT THE CYLINDER CONTAINED UN1075 LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS.  THERE WAS A 2-PAGE MSDS INSIDE THE BOX, AS WELL AS SEVERAL TAGS THAT STATED THAT HC-12A WAS INSIDE THE CYLINDER.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX.  THERE WERE NO DIRECTIONAL ARROWS ON THE BOX.  THE BOX WAS LOADED ON ITS SIDE WHEN THE CLERK FOUND IT, SINCE THE LOADER HAD NO INDICATION OF WHICH WAY THE PACKAGE SHOULD BE LOADED.  WE CALLED HMSC - THE REFERENCE NUMBER FOR THIS CALL IS 485146.
column169: SHIPPER FOLLOWUP.

column168: Unit was traveling North on I-65. When he topped a hill, traffic was stopped. Driver applied the brakes and vehicle began to hydroplane. He could not get stopped in time. To avoid hitting the other vehicles, he veered into the median. The unit overturned. The dome lids on the cargo tank began leaking diesel fuel. Cullman County Hazmat responded to the scene and began the containment process. SWS environmental was also dispatched to the scene for remediation purposes. ADEM sent an official to the scene to oversee the process. The dome lids leaked for approximately 2 hours.
column169: Driver has been reprimanded for following too close.

column168: On the morning of 07/22/11 at approximately 0330 a SJVR conductor was walking by a cut of cars in track 4602 in downtown Fresno, CA.  He noticed that tank car UTLX 130508 had vapor venting from the top of the car and thatthere was foul smell in the air. T he American Rail Dispatching Center emergency line was called to assist with allregulatory notifications. Fresno Fire Department responded to the scene and secured the area around the tank car.  SJVR managers Robert Jones and Robert Colvin responded to the scene as well and assisted emergency servicepersonnel with the paperwork and hazardous materials information. The customer that the railcar was destined forwas contacted to Inform them of the situation.The Fire Department mounted the tank car and inspected the origin of the venting vapor.  They found that there was an open tube with threads on the top of it that was open to the contents of the car. They capped the tube with aplastic bag to prevent any further vapors from venting.  A crew from the customer (Basic Chemical) arrived and performed an inspection on the railcar. They determined thatthe rupture valve assembly (Quick Inspection Safely Valve) was cracked from the base to the vent ports and the top of that holds a frangible disk and plug was completely missing.  The tube leading from the vent ports on the bottom ofthe assembly to the top was cracked as well.  They said that it looked like the metal bolts that secured the assemblyto tank car had been over tightened and that this had compromised the plastic assembly.The repair crew took a rupture valve assembly from another railcar in their facility and brought it to the location of theUTLX 130508 and replaced the valve.  Note: Scott Lewis at Basic Chemical reported 0 product lost from shipper to final destination based on unloading.
