column58: O-Ring or Seals; O-Ring or Seals
column62: Defective Component or Device; Human Error
column168: During a transfer of anhydrous ammonia at the EME Homer City plant, an o-ring contained in the rotating face of a mechanical seal assembly of the Blackmeer transfer pump cracked and allowed anhydrous ammonia to spew out of the pump.  The operator was standing near by and was able to shut down the pump and close the internal valve to prevent further release of product.  Approximately 10 litres released from the seal assembly.  A mechanical fact finding of the pump was performed and the failed component was determined to be the inner sealface o-ring of the mechanical seal assembly.  It had been replaced on 07/12/2011 at a Transport Canada (25-600) certified repair facility (ProPar(1978) in Aylmer, ON.  Closer examination of the o-ring revealed that a cut had compromised the mechanical seal and led to the release.  The cause of the failure could not be determined with complete certainty.  Either the o-ring was cut originally prior to the install or it was kinked when it was installed on 07/12/2011. Three full deliveries with the pump were executed prior to this incident without failure.  As a result we believe the root cause to be human error during the installation process.
column169: Further to the investigation we have asked the repair facility to use special care when fitting the mechanical seals over the threaded shafts of the LPG pumps. Prior to installation the mechanical seal is lubricated with a special compound and all o-rings are examined for defects.  The process involves carefully sliding it over the shaft while taking care to not cut, kink or tear the inner o-ring.  Once installed it is impossible to see the inner ring.  Only during the test and use phase can it be measured.  No further action will result from this isolated incident.

column168: SINCLAIR DRIVER, BRENT HUTZELL, ARRIVED AT THE BULK PLANT OWNED BY BLAKESBURG OIL TO BEGIN UNLOADING GASOLINE AND DIESEL. BRENT WALKED AROUND THE TRUCK AND UNLOADING RACK TO LOOK FOR ANY PROBLEMS. BRENT THEN HOOKED UP THE UNLOADING HOSE FOR GASOLINE TO BEGIN PUMPING OFF THE GASOLINE. BRENT WENT AND STARTED UP THE TRUCK AND ENGAGED THE PTO TO START THE PUMPING OPERATION WITH THE ENGINE AT ABOUT 500 RPM IDLE. BRENT THEN WALKED AROUND THE PUMP AND HOSES TO MAKE SURE THAT THERE WERE NO LEAKS, AND WHEN NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED GOT BACK IN THE TRUCK. BRENT THEN INCREASED THE RPM OF THE MOTOR FROM INSIDE THE TRUCK, AND ALL OF A SUDDEN THE ENGINE RACED TO "MAYBE 5000 RPM", SO BRENT TURNED OFF THE IGNITION, THEN GASOLINE STARTED COMING DOWN FROM THE PIPE ABOVE THE TRUCK, THE ENGINE THEN BLEW FROM THE EXCESSIVE RPM AND THE GASOLINE STARTED ON FIRE AROUND THE TRUCK. A PERSON WATCHING THE INCIDENT SAID THAT BRENT CLIMBED FROM THE TRUCK AND COLLAPSED, THE FIRE ENGULFED THE CAB OF THE TRUCK. IT WASN'T UNTIL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SHOWED UP AND STARTED SPRAYING THE CAB FIRE WITH WATER THAT THE FIRE SPREAD TO THE TRAILER AND STARTED THE TRAILER ON FIRE.
column169: THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE IS CURRENTLY BEING INVESTIGATED BY AN OUTSIDE INVESITGATOR, ALONG WITH THE INSURANCE COMPANY FOR BLAKESBURG OIL. INITIALLY THE CAUSE IS BEING BLAMED ON THE LACK OF A CHECK VAVLE IN THE GASOLINE LINE. THE VALVES WAS SUPPOSED TO HAVE BEEN INSTALLED, BUT WAS NEVER INSTALLED BY THE BY BLAKESBURG OIL OR THE COMPANY THEY HAD HIRED TO DO WORK ON THE LOADING/UNLOADING FACILITY.

column168: THE MORNING OF JULY 1, 2011; EDWARDS OIL WAS MAKING A ROUTINE DELIVERY TO THE EQUIPMENT TANK AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 AM. AS DRIVER BOB ZIESMER APPROACHED THE TANK TO WHERE THE FUEL WAS TO BE UNLOADED HE NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A LARGE, STANDING WATER POOL BLOCKING DIRECT ACCESS TO THE TANK. MR. ZIESMER HAD MADE THIS DELIVERY MANY TIMES PREVIOUSLY AND KNEW FROM PAST EXPERIENCE THAT WHEN THAT AREA GETS WET THAT THERE IS A GOOD LIKELIHOOD THAT THE TRUCK WILL GET STUCK IN THE SOFT, WET MATERIAL. OTHER DRIVERS HAD GOTTEN STUCK IN THE SAME AREA PREVIOUSLY AND HAD TO BE PULLED OUT WITH EQUIPMENT FROM MIDWEST ENERGY. TO ACCESS THE TANK AREA, MR. ZIESMER HAD TO PULL AROUND THE LARGE, WET AREA OF STANDING WATER AND IN HIS MANEUVER TOWARD THE TANK ENDED UP BACKING HIS TANKER INTO THE EQUIPMENT BAY. AS MR. ZIESMER PULLED OUT OF THE BAY, HE HAD TO TURN THE TRACTOR IN ORDER TO MANEUVER TOWARD THE TANK. UNFORTUNATELY, MR. ZIESMER TURNED TOO QUICKLY OR SHARPLY AND AS HE PULLED FURTHER OUT OF THE BAY, THE TANKER COMPARTMENT WAS RIPPED OPEN ABOUT MIDWAY UP BY A VERTICAL STEEL POST THAT ACTED AS AN OVERHEAD DOOR BUMPER. APPROXIMATELY 700 GALLONS OF THE COMPARTMENT CONTENTS OF DIESEL FUEL ESCAPED. FORTUNATELY, THE MAJORITY OF THE FUEL RAN BACK INTO THE CONCRETE LINED EQUIPMENT BY FROM WHICH MR. ZIESMER WAS EXITING FROM AND WAS CONTAINED. A SMALL AMOUNT RAN FORWARD AND INTO THE AREA MADE UP OF DIRT AND COAL. MR. ZIESMER INITIATED CLEANUP OF THE SPILL AND NOTIFIED PERSONNEL AT MIDWEST ENERGY AND HE ALSO INITIATED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.    EDWARDS EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS WERE CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED AT APPROXIMATELY 4AM BY EDWARDS OILS GENERAL MANAGER MR. BOB SKALKO. MR. JOE PALO IS AN ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER FOR GOLDER AND ASSOCIATES AND WAS TO DIRECT AND INVESTIGATE THE EXTENT OF CLEANUP NEEDED AND OSI ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED WITH A VACUUM RECOVERY TRUCK TO RECOVER THE FREE PRODUCT AND SUCK UP ANY LIQUID "SLURRY" MIX OF OIL, DIRT, AND COAL FINES. IN ADDITION, EDWARDS DISPATCHED ANOTHER COMPANY TRUCK WITH ADDITIONAL CLEANUP MATERIALS AND LABOR TO HELP OUT IN THE CLEANUP PROCESS AND REMOVE THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER COMPARTMENT. EDWARDS ALSO NOTIFIED WISCONSIN DNR AND THE FEDERAL NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.     THE MAJORITY OF THE EMERGENCY RECOVERY OF THE FREE PRODUCT AND SLURRY MIX WAS DONE BY 10AM AND ALL THAT REMAINED WAS TO REMOVE BETWEEN 10-20 YARDS OF A DIRT/COAL MIX THAT THE DIESEL HAD DRAINED INTO BUT WAS TOO DEEP OR DRY TO BE RECOVERED BY A VACUUM TRUCK. A SMALL BACKHOE WAS COMMISSIONED TO EXCAVATE THIS AREA AND MR. JOE PALO WAS ON-HAND TO SUPERVISE THE CLEANUP. MIDWEST ENERGY RETAINED ENVIRONMENTAL TROUBLESHOOTERS TO SUPERVISE MR. PALO'S EFFORTS AND RECOMMENDATIONS.    THE RECOVERED CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE TESTED AND THEN SENT TO WASTE MANAGEMENT'S DISPOSAL SITE IN COTTON, MN.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: APPROXIMATELY FOUR DAYS PRIOR TO THE DATE (JULY 6, 2011) OF THE INCIDENT SMITH SYSTEMS TRANSPORTATION, INC DRIVER DROPPED OFF A TRAILER WHICH HAD BEEN LOADED WITH HAZARDOUS WASTE BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL. THE TEMPORARY HOLDING LOT IS AT 8542 ELDER CREEK ROAD, SACRAMENTO, CA WHERE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. ON JULY 6, ON OR ABOUT 7:30 AM TWO EMPLOYEES AT AN ADJACENT BUSINESS OBSERVED "WHITE SMOKE" FROM THE TOP REAR DOORS OF THE TRAILER. THEY CONTACTED THE OWNER OF THE LOT. THE OWNER CONTACTED 911, SMITH SYSTEMS PERSONNEL AND BEGAN MOVING OTHER TRAILERS THAT WERE LOCATED THERE AWAY FROM THE AFFECTED TRAILER. THE SACRAMENTO POLICE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED TO DIRECT TRAFFIC AND EVACUATE GENEREAL PUBLIC IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND TREATED THE MATERIAL. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL FIRE WAS CONTAINED AND NOT A THREAT. A FEW HOURS LATER THE MATERIAL WERE ONCE AGAIN ON FIRE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED TO TREAT A FIRE THAT WAS BURNING THE ENTIRE TRAILER. THOUSANDS OF GALLONS OF WATER AND SUPPRESSENT WERE USED TO PUT OUT THE FIRE. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL INDICATED THAT THE FIRE WAS OUT AROUND 9:00 PM. column168: APPROXIMATELY FOUR DAYS PRIOR TO THE DATE (JULY 6, 2011) OF THE INCIDENT SMITH SYSTEMS TRANSPORTATION, INC DRIVER DROPPED OFF A TRAILER WHICH HAD BEEN LOADED WITH HAZARDOUS WASTE BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL. THE TEMPORARY HOLDING LOT IS AT 8542 ELDER CREEK ROAD, SACRAMENTO, CA WHERE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. ON JULY 6, ON OR ABOUT 7:30 AM TWO EMPLOYEES AT AN ADJACENT BUSINESS OBSERVED "WHITE SMOKE" FROM THE TOP REAR DOORS OF THE TRAILER. THEY CONTACTED THE OWNER OF THE LOT. THE OWNER CONTACTED 911, SMITH SYSTEMS PERSONNEL AND BEGAN MOVING OTHER TRAILERS THAT WERE LOCATED THERE AWAY FROM THE AFFECTED TRAILER. THE SACRAMENTO POLICE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED TO DIRECT TRAFFIC AND EVACUATE GENEREAL PUBLIC IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND TREATED THE MATERIAL. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL FIRE WAS CONTAINED AND NOT A THREAT. A FEW HOURS LATER THE MATERIAL WERE ONCE AGAIN ON FIRE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED TO TREAT A FIRE THAT WAS BURNING THE ENTIRE TRAILER. THOUSANDS OF GALLONS OF WATER AND SUPPRESSENT WERE USED TO PUT OUT THE FIRE. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL INDICATED THAT THE FIRE WAS OUT AROUND 9:00 PM. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WER ON SITE WITH THE REMOVAL PROCESS UNTIL JULY 9. ONCE THE FIRE WAS OUT, CLEAN HARBORS PERSONNEL BEGAN REMOVAL OF THE TRAILER AND REMANING CONTENT IMMEDIATELY AND THIS WAS COMPLETED BY JULY 10. CLEAN UP AND REMEDIATION OF THE AREA AND SOIL WAS COMPLETED IN MID-NOVEMBER 2011. SEVERAL CUBIC FEET OF ASPHALT AND SOIL WERE REMOVED. CLEAN SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED INTO INCIDENT AREA AND CORE SAMPLES OF THE SOIL WERE TAKEN PERIODICALLY TO INSURE THE REMEDIATION WAS SUCCESSFUL.

THE SACRAMENTO POLICE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED TO DIRECT TRAFFIC AND EVACUATE GENEREAL PUBLIC IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND TREATED THE MATERIAL. A FEW HOURS LATER THE MATERIAL WERE ONCE AGAIN ON FIRE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED TO TREAT A FIRE THAT WAS BURNING THE ENTIRE TRAILER. THE OWNER CONTACTED 911, SMITH SYSTEMS PERSONNEL AND BEGAN MOVING OTHER TRAILERS THAT WERE LOCATED THERE AWAY FROM THE AFFECTED TRAILER. THE OWNER CONTACTED 911, SMITH SYSTEMS PERSONNEL AND BEGAN MOVING OTHER TRAILERS THAT WERE LOCATED THERE AWAY FROM THE AFFECTED TRAILER. THE SACRAMENTO POLICE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED TO DIRECT TRAFFIC AND EVACUATE GENEREAL PUBLIC IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND TREATED THE MATERIAL. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL FIRE WAS CONTAINED AND NOT A THREAT. A FEW HOURS LATER THE MATERIAL WERE ONCE AGAIN ON FIRE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED TO TREAT A FIRE THAT WAS BURNING THE ENTIRE TRAILER. THOUSANDS OF GALLONS OF WATER AND SUPPRESSENT WERE USED TO PUT OUT THE FIRE. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL INDICATED THAT THE FIRE WAS OUT AROUND 9:00 PM. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WER ON SITE WITH THE REMOVAL PROCESS UNTIL JULY 9. ONCE THE FIRE WAS OUT, CLEAN HARBORS PERSONNEL BEGAN REMOVAL OF THE TRAILER AND REMANING CONTENT IMMEDIATELY AND THIS WAS COMPLETED BY JULY 10. CLEAN UP AND REMEDIATION OF THE AREA AND SOIL WAS COMPLETED IN MID-NOVEMBER 2011. SEVERAL CUBIC FEET OF ASPHALT AND SOIL WERE REMOVED. CLEAN SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED INTO INCIDENT AREA AND CORE SAMPLES OF THE SOIL WERE TAKEN PERIODICALLY TO INSURE THE REMEDIATION WAS SUCCESSFUL.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, TWO CARTONS WERE FOUND DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  THE RELEASE WAS PROPERLY MANAGED.  THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PLACED INTO A LINED SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: ALWAYS BLOCK AND BRACE FREIGHT TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: Upon Arrival no product was actively leaking. There was product stain around the liquid valve plug. The Liquid valve plug was teflon taped and secured. Intruction were given to the shipper to bad order the car for testing of the valves. The car was released back into transportation with no further incident.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: SKID THAT THE SHIPPER PLACED THE FREIGHT ON WAS OLD.  THE FREIGHT FELL THROUGHT THE SKID WHEN IT BROKE.  AS THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE FREIGHT HE FORKED THE PAILS.
column169: SHIPPER NEEDS TO USE BETTER SKIDS WHEN PREPARING THEIR FREIGHT FOR SHIPPING.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column25: DOW CHEMICAL OWNS PRODUCT IN THE TANKS
column168: EVENT # 31129 SPILL - 3 GAL HAZ # 3082 - TM, BRAD VICKNAIR CALLED - STATED THERE WAS PUMP SEAL FAILURE YESTERDAY OF A STORAGE TANK.  THE CAUSE WAS PRESSURE INCREASED INSIDE PIPELINE ABOVE 35 PSI AND BELOW 100 PSI CAUSING THE INSIDE LIP OF A TWO PART SEAL INSIDE THE PUMP TO FAIL.  TO CORRECT THE PROBLEM, THE TERMINAL INCREASED THE TUBING SIZE FROM 1/4* ID TO 1/2 AND HEAT TRACED AND INSULATED THE TUBING.  NO FURTHER ISSUES.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column17: QUALITY CARRIERS INC VIA IT'S AFFILIATE, QCI - NEW CASTLE, DE
column168: EVENT # 31157 OCCUP/AX.INJ - LOADED - DRIVER HEARD AIR AND WAS LO0SINING THE EAR WHEN A MIST SPRAYED OUT AND GOT INTO HIS EYE...HE WENT TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM AND THEY GAVE HIM OINTMENT TO PUT IN EYES.  HE IS HAVING NO FURTHER ISSUES.  ALL PROPER PPE GEAR WAS ON

column168: Train QRVWCB 26, Derailed 22 rail cars at mile post 423.3 located near 94th St. East and East Ave. T.     Five rail cars containing residue of hazardous materials were involved. The following is a list of tank car numbers:    QFFX 25223 - Hydrogen Flouride, Anhydrous  DOWX 6161 - Xylene  DOWX 74069 - Butyl Acrylates  DOWX 80715 - Chlorine  DOWX 80825 - Chlorine    All tank cars were inspected, no releases occurred.

column168: At approximately 1800 hours on 07/12/2011, the Supervisor noticed ethanol leaking from the top of the first railcar located at 1 siding B track (opposite road side) which was chalked, secured and unloading as a string of rail cars into a facility above ground storage tank.  The path of the ethanol ran down the sides of the railcar to the ground.  The spill left a 4-foot wide visible path down the sides of the tank car.  The drip pan under the rail car caught a majority of the ethanol, but it overflowed and product impacted the soil.  The total square footage of impacted soil was approximately 8 feet.  The estimated amount of ethanol that impacted the soil is 20 gallons.  The RQ for ethanof is 15 gallons. The block valve on the line connecting to the product hose was closed immediately, stopping the product from continuing to fill the rail car.  Agency notifications were made, NRC Incident # 928484 assigned.  The impacted rock and soil were remediated and placed into a labeled satellite drum.  The block valve that connects to the block valve was then locked out.  The tank car, NATX-364454, was hooked up for off-load into Tank 95-2, along with 11 other ethanol cars all sharing the same common line.  The check valve, located behind the block valve at spot 5B where the car was hooked up, didn't hold. Investigation revealed that a small rock, likely inside the rail car or capped unloading hose, entered the system and wedged against a check valve, forcing it to remain open.  When the operator began opening the block valves for each ethanol car, product began to flow in the opposite direction due to the path of least resistance.  The tank was closed at this point and the ethanol lines remained full until remediation was completed and Supervisor deemed situation safe to continue.
column169: ROOT CAUSE: ROCK ENTERED SYSTEM AND JAMMED CHECK VALVE OPEN.  CORRECTIVE ACTION PERFORMED:                                                                         1. REMEDIATE ALL IMPACTED SOIL INTO DRUM.  2. PLACE DRUM IN PROPER WASTE LOCATION AND LABEL FOR DISPOSAL.  3. LOCK OUT THE BLOCK VALVE WITH THE DEFECTIVE CHECK VALVE.  4. CONDUCT PM ON CHECK VALVES TO ENSURE PROPER FLOW PER PRESCRIBED PM SCHEDULE.

column168: Driver called in that he observed liquid coming out from inside his trailer while traveling on I-84 in Putnam County NY at approx the 55 mile marker east bound. Driver immediately pulled over when safe to do so and took immediate action with his on board spill kit. Driver notified his dispatcher who in turn notified a representative from our Loss Prevention Department who contacted one of our Emergency Spill Responders (ER)to mitigate the unintention release at the scene. The local police and fire departments responded as well to help mitigate and contain the spill. There were 6 plastic IBCs in metal cages on board the trailer along with other miscellaneous freight. Apparently the blocking and bracing of the IBCs failed and as a result a pallet that was being used as dunnage inbetween two of the totes punctured one of the IBCs about midpoint. The piece of wood that punctured the IBC actually worked as a plug as well preventing mass evacuation of the IBC where it was punctured. The ER was able to pump the remaining fluid into four poly overpack containers and the material that had spilled out was neutralized and cleaned with absorbents and actually removal/replacement of contaminated soil as well.
column169: When blocking and bracing need to properly place dunnage being used to prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring. Will use this example in future training meetings to prevent future unintentional releases.

column168: I ARRIVED AT THE LANSING BOARD OF WATER AND LIGHTS PLANT AT 7:45 A.M. AND MET WITH CHRIS THOMPSON A FILL-IN OPERATOR. HE WAS BUSY WITH SOME DUTIES SO I WAITED A FEW MINUTES. HE CAME BACK OUT OF THE BUILDING AND I TOLD HIM THAT I HAD A LOAD OF CHLORINE BLEACH AND HE WENT BACK IN THE BUILDING TO GET AN ADAPTOR AND HE PUT IT ON THE PIPELINE TO THE TANK SO MY HOSE WOULD HOOKUP. THEN HE WENT BACK INTO THE BUILDING AND I HOOKED UP ON MY UNLOADING HOSE AND AIR HOSE FROM MY TRUCK TO THE TRAILER. THEN CHRIS CAME OUT WITH MY PAPER THEY CALL A TAILGATE FROM THAT I SIGNED AND I ASKED IF HE WANTED TO SIGN MY BILL OF LADING AND HE SAID NOT UNTIL THE UNLOAD WAS COMPLETED. AT THAT TIME I STARTED TO OPEN MY TRAILER VALVES TO BEGIN UNLOADING THE LOAD AND THEN CHRIS WENT BACK INTO THE BUILDING FOR MORE DUTIES AND I WENT BACK TO MY TRUCK TO SET THE R.P.M.'S FOR UNLOADING THEN I DID A WALK AROUMD THE TRAILER AND EVERYTHING WAS OK. AFTER ABOUT 10 MINUTES CHRIS CAME BACK OUT OF THE BUILDING AND SAID THERE MUST BE A LEAK BECAUSE HE COULD SMELL THE FUMES. AT THAT TIME I CHECKED MY HOSE FOR LEAKS AND THEN I WENT TO TURN OFF THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE AT THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND THEN I SHUT MY TRUCK ENGINE OFF. I WENT BACK TO CHECK WITH CHRIS AND THEN I SMELLED THE FUMES AND THEN CHRIS REALIZED THAT HE TOLD ME THE WRONG HOOKUP LOCATION. AT THAT TIME WE BOTH WALKED AWAY FROM THE AREA. CHRIS THEN CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR, MARILYN. MARILYN CAME OUT TO GIVE CHRIS A AIR PACK TO PUT ON AND HE WENT BACK INTO THE BUILDING TO SHUT OFF THE TANK VALVE. WHEN HE CAME BACK OUT THEN MARILYN LEFT TO GO AND SECURE THE FRONT GATE. CHRIS AND I WALKED FURTHER AWAY AND THEN ANOTHER MAN CAME AND WE WERE TOLD TO SIT IN THE CAR. AFTER A FEW MINUTES MARILYN CAME BACK OUT TO THE CAR AND GOT AN AIR PACK AND PUT IT ON AND WENT UP CLOSE TO THE DOOR TO THE BUILDING. WHEN SHE GOT BACK SHE GOT IN HER CAR AND WENT BACK TO THE FRONT OFFICE. AFTER A FEW MINUTES MARILYN CAME BACK TO WHERE WE WERE SITTING AND PARKED HER CAR AND GOT IN THE CAR WITH US AND TOLD THE DRIVER TO TAKE US TO SPARROW HOSPITAL FOR CHECKUPS.

column168: ON SUNDAY, 7/24/11, AT APPROXIMATELY 1500, LIQUID HYDROGEN (LH2) TEAM DRIVERS LEFT THE ST. MARY'S, PA DEPOT IN TRACTOR 95068 AND TRAILER 48371 AND PROCEEDED TO CUSTOMER DUFERCO - FARRELL CORPORATION LOCATED AT 15 ROEMER BLVD. FARRELL, PA 16121 TO DELIVER PRODUCT.    AT APPROXIMATELY 1730, THE TEAM DRIVERS ARRIVED AT THE DURFERCO FACILITY AND PROCEEDED TO DELIVER TO THE CUSTOMER. AT APPROXIMATELY 1850, THE ON DUTY DRIVER COMPLETED THE DELIVERY AND WAS READY TO DEPRESSURIZE THE TRAILER SO HE COULD REMOVE THE HOSE. HE STARTED TO TURN VENT VALVE (V-12) WHEN HE STARTED HEARING "SOUNDS HE NEVER HEARD BEFORE" AND SUDDENLY THE RELIEF SYSTEM DIVERTER VALVE (V-59) CAME APART. IMMEDIATELY, THE CONTENTS COMING OUT OF V-59 CAUGHT FIRE AND THE VACUUM CAPS LOCATED ON THE TOP, REAR OF THE TRAILER (ABOVE THE COLD END OF THE TRAILER) AND THE TOP FRONT OF THE TRAILER WERE DISLODGED AND FIRE PROCEEDED TO COME OUT OF THE OPENINGS.    AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, THE OFF DUTY DRIVER EXITED THE TRACTOR TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE TO THE OTHER DRIVER. AT APPOXIMATELY 1859, FIREFIGHTERS FROM THE FARRELL, PA FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON SCENE AND THE EMTS ARRIVED ON SCENE A SHORT TIME LATER. BOTH DRIVERS WERE EVALUATED BY THE EMT'S AT THE INCIDENT SCENE AND WERE TAKEN BY AMBULANCE TO LOCAL HOSPITALS FOR FURTHER EVALUATION.     AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURRED, THE AIR LIQUIDE SAFETY MANAGER AND ST. MARY'S, PA MECHANIC WERE IN PHONE CONTACT WITH FARRELL, PA FIRE CHIEF JOE SANTELL TO ASSESS THE SITUATION AND PROVIDE SUPPORT UNTIL THE ST. MARY'S DEPOT MANAGER AND THE AREA SAFETY SPECIALIST ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. THE FIRE CHIEF WAS DIRECTED TO USE UNMANNED HOSES AND KEEP WATER ON THE CUSTOMER STORAGE VESSEL, THE LH2 TRAILER, AND THE TRACTOR UNTIL THE FIRE IN THE TRAILER BURNED ITSELF OUT. THE FIRE CHIEF WAS ALSO DIRECTED TO SHUT THE CUSTOMER EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF BUTTON LOCATED ON THE REAR CORNER OF THE INSTALLATION FENCE, AND ONE OF HIS FIREFIGHTERS WAS ABLE TO GET TO THE BOX AND PUSH THE BUTTON.    AT APPROXIMATELY 0630 (MONDAY 7/25/11), FLAMES WERE NO LONGER EVIDENT. AT APPROXIMATELY 0715, THE SAFETY SPECIALIST ON THE SCENE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DECLARED THE SCENE SECURE AND AIR LIQUIDE INITIATED IS INVESTIGATION AT APPROX 0730.    BASED ON THE INFORMATION OBTAINED DURING THE INVESTIGATION, THE INVESTIGATION TEACH CONCLUDES THAT:    1) SUFFICENT AMBIENT AIR FOR COMBUSTION ENTERED THE SYSTEM BY DIFFUSION AND CONVECTION.    2) AMBIENT AIR CONDENSED AND FROZE AS IT APPROACHED THE TRAILER'S INNER VESSEL.    3) SOLID FROZEN AIR WAS TRAPPED IN THE 3 INCH SCH 5 304SS PIPING CONNECTED TO THE PRESSURE VESSEL (PV) NOZZLE.    4) WHEN THE DRIVER TURNED THE 2" VENT VALVE (V-12) OPEN TO A HIGH DISCHARGE RATE TO DEPRESSURIZE THE TRAILER, THE SOLID FROZEN AIR WAS DISTURBED AND SUFFICIENT FRICTION CAUSED AN IGNITION OF THE HYDROGEN AND AIR IN THE 3 INCH SCH 5 304SS PIPING CONNECTED TO THE PV NOZZLE.     5) DETONATION OCCURRED IN THE HORIZONTAL 3 INCH SCH 5 304SS PIPING CAUSING A FACTURE AT THE PV NOZZLE
column169: - UPDATE PROCEDURES REGARDING THE OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF LH2 TRAILERS. RE-TRAIN ALL DRIVERS ON THE REVISIONS TO THE PROCEDURES.    - REEMPHASIZE WITH LH2 DRIVERS THE IMPORTANCE OF RECOGNIZING WHAT HAZARDOUS ENERGY THEY MAY ENCOUNTER WHILE PERFORMING THEIR TASKS AND WHAT STEPS TO BE TAKEN TO HELP PREVENT BEING INJURED FROM SUDDEN RELEASE OF THAT ENERGY.    - PERFORM PROCESS HAZARD ANALYSIS (PHA) ON LH2 TRAILERS IN FLEET TO DETERMINE THE PROBABILITY AND SEVERITY OF RISKS WITH THE EQUIPMENT AND TO DEVELOP CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO HELP PREVENT INJURY.
